Person 2 Checklist

Create your layer as “raw packet movement behind a stable API,” even before the real virtio device is finished.

1. Define the interface first.
    Create kernel/virtio_net.h
    Add bool net_send_raw(const uint8_t* data, size_t len);
    Add int net_recv_raw(uint8_t* out, size_t max_len);
    Add bool net_ready();
    Add void net_debug_dump_frame(const uint8_t* data, size_t len);
    Add a tiny integration boundary for Person 1, like bool nic_ready(); and void nic_kick_tx();

2. Define the core data structures.
    Add TX descriptor struct(s)
    Add RX descriptor struct(s)
    Add avail/used ring structs
    Add software-side queue state
    Add fixed-size packet buffer storage
    Add constants for queue size, max frame size, descriptor flags

3. Build the software queue manager.
    Implement TX enqueue logic
    Implement TX completion reclaim logic
    Implement RX dequeue logic
    Implement RX buffer recycle logic
    Track head/tail or producer/consumer indices cleanly
    Add safety checks for full/empty rings

4. Build a fake backend so you can work before Person 1 is done.
    Create kernel/virtio_net.cc
    Add a fake mode where TX just logs frames
    Add a fake RX injection path for test packets
    Simulate used-ring completion
    Make net_ready() return false gracefully if no backend is installed

5. Implement the public API.
    net_send_raw(...) should validate length, copy into a TX buffer, enqueue, and notify backend
    net_recv_raw(...) should return packet length, copy out data, and recycle the RX slot
    net_debug_dump_frame(...) should print bytes in a readable hex format
    Return clean failure values instead of panicking on expected conditions

6. Agree on the contract with Person 1.
    Person 1 should expose a minimal “device is initialized” signal
    Person 1 should expose queue hookup points, not protocol logic
    You should not depend on PCI scanning details in your packet API
    Keep all virtqueue/ring logic on your side if possible

7. Agree on the contract with Person 3.
    Person 3 should only call net_send_raw(...) and net_recv_raw(...)
    Person 3 should not know about descriptors, MMIO, or queue indices
    Decide now what net_recv_raw(...) returns on “no packet available”

8. Add debug output early.
    Log TX enqueue index changes
    Log RX dequeue index changes
    Log packet lengths
    Add optional frame dumps for first 64 bytes
    Keep debug prints easy to disable

9. Test without the real NIC.
    Inject a fake Ethernet frame and confirm net_recv_raw(...) returns it correctly
    Send a fake frame and confirm TX ring state advances correctly
    Verify descriptors get recycled
    Verify full-ring and empty-ring behavior
    Verify oversized packets are rejected safely

10. Integration pass after Person 1 lands.
    Replace fake notify/check functions with real virtio hooks
    Confirm queue memory addresses are handed to the device correctly
    Confirm used entries are observed correctly
    Confirm TX kick and RX refill behavior works on real hardware

Suggested files

    kernel/virtio_net.h
    kernel/virtio_net.cc

Done condition

Raw Ethernet frames can be queued for transmit
Raw Ethernet frames can be pulled from receive buffers
Higher layers can use your API without knowing anything about the NIC internals
Your code still works in fake mode if hardware bring-up is not ready



